The paper deals with geometric optimization techniques for computing polygon partitions, point covers, interval covers, square and rectangle covers, and K-centers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of dynamic programming and efficient data structures also suggests that the paper could belong to the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The optimization techniques presented in the paper could also be relevant to discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and game theory (cs.GT) sub-categories. Finally, the paper's focus on practical applications suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
